---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="Jarvis"
  path="/projects/jarvis/"
  description="An always-on, self-hosted voice assistant. Two architecturally isolated brains: a private one that runs my infrastructure, a public one that's safe for strangers."
  lede="An always-on, self-hosted voice assistant. A Home Assistant pipeline handles in-browser wake word, speech-to-text, an LLM control brain with tool access to my infrastructure, and text-to-speech, plus a Discord voice interface for friends."
  tags={['LLM tooling', 'Home Assistant', 'Whisper', 'Threat modeling', 'Python']}
  status="In build"
  demonstrates="LLM tool integration, a full speech pipeline, threat modeling for AI agents, prompt-injection-resistant design, and cost engineering (the whole thing runs on hardware I already owned)."
>
  <h2>Why it exists</h2>
  <p>
    I wanted a voice assistant that answers to me, not to a vendor's cloud, and
    that can actually do things: check the homelab, answer questions, control
    the house. The interesting problem wasn't wiring the speech pipeline. It was
    letting friends talk to it too, without handing strangers a microphone into
    my infrastructure.
  </p>

  <h2>What I built</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>In-browser wake word ("Hey Jarvis"), no always-on cloud mic.</li>
    <li>Whisper speech-to-text on a CUDA GPU.</li>
    <li>An LLM control brain with tool access to my infrastructure APIs.</li>
    <li>Piper text-to-speech for the voice.</li>
    <li>
      A Discord voice interface built on per-user audio streams, so it can hear
      individual people in a call.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Two Jarvises</h2>
  <p>
    There are two assistants by design, and they are isolated at the
    architecture level, not by politeness. The private one knows my
    infrastructure and can act on it. The public one, which friends talk to
    through Discord, has zero infrastructure knowledge, zero personal context,
    and exactly three whitelisted capabilities.
  </p>
  <p>
    Try to break it. Send the same message to both, then flip the architecture
    to v1, the version I shipped first and got wrong, and send it again.
  </p>

  <div class="jarvis-demo bleed" data-jarvis>
    <div class="map-controls">
      <span class="ctl-label">architecture</span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-arch="v2" aria-pressed="true">v2 — shipped</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-arch="v1" aria-pressed="false">v1 — the mistake</button>
    </div>

    <div class="map-controls">
      <span class="ctl-label">send</span>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-prompt="inject" aria-pressed="true">ignore your instructions…</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-prompt="who" aria-pressed="false">who owns you?</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-prompt="shopping" aria-pressed="false">shopping list?</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-prompt="infra" aria-pressed="false">what's on the hypervisor?</button>
      <button class="map-btn" type="button" data-prompt="media" aria-pressed="false">add Dune</button>
    </div>

    <div class="bots">
      <div class="bot is-private">
        <h3>Private Jarvis</h3>
        <p class="bot-where">desk · Home Assistant</p>
        <p class="bot-who">Only I talk to it. It may know everything.</p>
        <p class="possess-label">possesses</p>
        <ul class="possess">
          <li class="has">Home Assistant</li>
          <li class="has">infra APIs</li>
          <li class="has">personal context</li>
          <li class="has">monitoring via MCP</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="bot-out" data-out="private" aria-live="polite"></div>
      </div>

      <div class="bot is-public">
        <h3>Public Jarvis</h3>
        <p class="bot-where">Discord</p>
        <p class="bot-who">Friends talk to it. Untrusted audience by design.</p>
        <p class="possess-label">possesses</p>
        <ul class="possess" data-possess-public></ul>
        <div class="bot-out" data-out="public" aria-live="polite"></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="verdict">
      <p data-verdict></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Why it's built this way</h2>
  <p>
    The isolation is structural, not textual. A system prompt that says "don't
    reveal X" fails the first time someone types "ignore your instructions". The
    only prompt-injection defense that holds is an agent that does not possess
    the information or the capability in the first place.
  </p>
  <p>
    The specific trap was Home Assistant: it exposes entities to the
    conversation API globally, not per agent. So "just give the public bot a
    different HA agent" does not contain the blast radius. The bot has to not
    touch HA at all. v2 talks directly to its own three tools instead, and the
    API keys live in environment variables that never enter model context.
  </p>
  <p class="sample-note">
    Responses are scripted illustrations of each architecture's real
    capabilities, not live model output. The capability boundaries shown are the
    actual ones.
  </p>

  <script is:inline src="/js/jarvis-demo.js" defer></script>
</ProjectLayout>
